    "description": "Warfarin is an anticoagulant medication that is commonly used to prevent and treat blood clots in conditions such as deep vein thrombosis (DVT), pulmonary embolism (PE), and in patients with atrial fibrillation or certain types of heart valve replacements. It works by inhibiting the vitamin K epoxide reductase enzyme, which is necessary for the synthesis of several clotting factors, ultimately reducing the formation of clots in the blood vessels.",
    
    "uses": "Warfarin is primarily used for the prevention of new blood clots and the treatment of existing clots. It is often prescribed to patients with atrial fibrillation to reduce the risk of stroke, as well as to individuals recovering from surgeries that might lead to thrombus formation. Additionally, it can be used for patients with mechanical heart valves to prevent thromboembolic complications.\n\nIn some cases, Warfarin is used off-label for other conditions, such as managing certain types of vasculitis or preventing complications in patients with certain genetic disorders that lead to increased clot formation.",
    
    "side effects": [
      "Bleeding: Increased risk of bleeding events, which can be minor (such as nosebleeds or gum bleeding) or major (such as gastrointestinal bleeding or intracranial hemorrhage).",
      "Bruising: Patients may experience easy bruising due to the anticoagulant effects of the medication.",
      "Skin rash: Some individuals may develop a skin rash or other allergic reactions.",
      "Liver function changes: Warfarin can affect liver function, leading to abnormal liver enzyme levels in some patients."
